## Code conventions

- Match surrounding code style, structure, and idioms exactly.
- Prefer reuse: search for an existing utility before writing a new one.
- Functions do one thing; name them for their effect, not their mechanism.
- No dead code, no commented-out blocks, no TODO without owner/condition.

## Naming

- Files and directories: kebab-case.
- Types and classes: PascalCase.
- Functions and variables: per-language idiom.

## Errors and boundaries

- Validate all inputs and external responses. Fail fast with actionable messages.
- Never swallow errors silently. Never log secrets.
- Respect module/layer boundaries from the architecture rules — no cross-layer imports.

## Testing

- Every behaviour change ships with a test (test the behaviour, not the implementation).
- A sprint's Definition of Done references the testing rule; Phase-8 audit checks it.

## Dependencies

- Justify before adding (size, maintenance, license). Pin versions.
- Before writing code against any third-party library, follow the Context7 rule below.

## Git

- Conventional Commits: `feat:` `fix:` `docs:` `refactor:` `test:` `chore:`.
- Small, reviewable commits. Branch off the default branch. Never commit secrets.
- Commit/push only when the human explicitly asks.

## Security

- Secrets only in env vars / per-developer config. Never in committed files.
- MCP configs use `${ENV_VAR}` placeholders. Least-privilege for filesystem/git MCP scopes.
- Treat all external input as untrusted.

## Design system

- All UI references tokens from `product/design-system.md` (`tokens.json` / `tokens.css`).
- Never hardcode colours, spacing, type sizes, or radii — always reference `--ds-*` vars.

## Context7 (mandatory before any third-party code)

1. Call `resolve-library-id` with the library name.
2. Call `get-library-docs` with the resolved id, version in use, and a topic filter.
3. Write code against the returned docs — not from memory.

Full rule and fallback procedure: `harness/rules/context7-usage.md`.

## Model intent (Windsurf collapses tiers to prose intent)

- Research / search / extraction → fastest available model.
- Writing code, docs, sprint artifacts → mid-tier model.
- Architecture / audit / code review / security → strongest available model.

